        <section id="paris">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">I</span>
                <h2>Paris</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">January 6–9</p>
            </div>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>We land at Charles de Gaulle in the blue hour of a January afternoon, that particular Parisian twilight that painters have been chasing for centuries. The taxi winds through the périphérique as the city reveals itself in fragments: the Sacré-Cœur glowing white on its hill, the Seine curving beneath bridges we'll walk across tomorrow, the apartment blocks with their zinc roofs and wrought-iron balconies, each window a small theater of French life.</p>

                <p>Our apartment is in the 9th arrondissement, on a street called Rue Moncey. Not the Paris of postcards—no Eiffel Tower views, no Marais cobblestones—but the Paris of Parisians. The neighborhood of Pigalle and the Folies Bergère, of corner bakeries that have been making the same croissants for three generations, of wine bars where nobody speaks English because nobody needs to. This is where we'll learn to breathe in a different rhythm.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="inline-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1511739001486-6bfe10ce65f4?w=1000&q=80" 
                     alt="Parisian cafe in winter" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>A café terrace in the 9th arrondissement, even in January</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>The first day is for recovery—that particular jet-lag state where everything feels slightly unreal, like walking through a film you've seen before. We'll find a café that becomes ours, order café crèmes and watch the neighborhood wake up, let the city come to us rather than chasing it.</p>

                <p>But by Wednesday, we're ready. The <strong>Maison Européenne de la Photographie</strong> first—three floors of images in a Marais mansion, one of Europe's great photography museums and almost unknown to tourists. Then across the river to the <strong>Musée de l'Orangerie</strong>, that small temple built specifically to house Monet's water lilies. Eight panels. Two oval rooms. The closest thing to meditation you can find in a museum. We'll sit there until the guards politely suggest we move on.</p>

                <p>Afternoon in the Tuileries, even in January. The gardens will be bare, the fountains still, the chairs stacked against the cold—but there's something perfect about Paris in its dormant season. The light is gentler. The crowds are gone. The city belongs to the people who live there.</p>

                <p>Dinner in Saint-Germain, because some clichés exist for a reason. We don't need to plan it. We'll walk until somewhere feels right.</p>
            </div>

