        <!-- Venice -->
        <section id="venice">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">II</span>
                <h2>Venice</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">January 9–13</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="full-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514890547357-a9ee288728e0?w=1400&q=80" 
                     alt="Venice canal in morning mist" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>The Grand Canal at dawn, before the city wakes</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Venice in January is a secret the city keeps from summer tourists. The cruise ships are gone. The gelato stands are shuttered. The acqua alta may flood the piazzas, but that's part of the magic—watching Venetians in rubber boots wade through St. Mark's Square like it's the most normal thing in the world, because to them it is.</p>

                <p>We're staying in Dorsoduro, the quiet belly of the city, where the Accademia and the Guggenheim are neighbors and the views across the Giudecca Canal make every sunset feel like a gift you didn't deserve. Our hotel is the <strong>Il Palazzo Experimental</strong>—a 16th-century palazzo reimagined by Dorothée Meilichzon, the designer who made the Experimental Group the most interesting hotel company in Europe. Terrazzo floors. Murano glass. A bar that serves better Negronis than most places in Milan.</p>

                <p>We'll spend four nights here, which sounds like a lot for a city you can walk across in an hour. But Venice doesn't work that way. Venice is not a city to see—it's a city to get lost in, to let swallow you whole, to surrender to until you stop trying to understand it and just exist inside it.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="inline-image right">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558618666-fcd25c85cd64?w=800&q=80" 
                     alt="Venetian architecture detail" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>Byzantine meets Gothic: a Dorsoduro palazzo window</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Saturday is for the Venetians—the ones who painted, the ones who collected. Morning at the <strong>Gallerie dell'Accademia</strong>: Bellini's altarpieces glowing with that impossible light, Giorgione's "Tempest" still mysterious after five hundred years, Veronese's "Feast in the House of Levi" so scandalous the Inquisition made him change the title. Afternoon at the <strong>Peggy Guggenheim Collection</strong>, that palazzo on the Grand Canal where an American heiress built one of the great modern art collections while scandalizing Venetian society and sleeping with most of the artists.</p>

                <p>Sunday we do the things you're supposed to do: St. Mark's Basilica, the Doge's Palace, the Bridge of Sighs. But we'll do them early, before the day-trippers arrive, when the mosaics catch the morning light and the palace feels like what it was—the seat of an empire that ruled the Mediterranean for a thousand years.</p>

                <p>And on Monday, the islands. <strong>Murano</strong> first, to watch glassblowers do what their families have done since the 13th century, when the furnaces were banished from Venice proper because they kept burning the city down. Then <strong>Burano</strong>, that fishing village where every house is painted a different color—originally so fishermen could find their way home through the fog, now so tourists can fill their Instagram feeds. We'll have lunch there, at some trattoria that serves whatever came out of the lagoon that morning, and we won't look at our phones once.</p>
            </div>

            <aside class="pull-quote">
                <p>Venice is not a city to see—it's a city to get lost in, to let swallow you whole.</p>
            </aside>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Tuesday morning, we leave. The water taxi will take us back to Marco Polo, and we'll watch the city recede into the lagoon, already planning when we'll come back. Everyone says that about Venice. Everyone means it.</p>
            </div>

