        <!-- Dolomites -->
        <section id="dolomites">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">III</span>
                <h2>The Dolomites</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">January 13–17</p>
            </div>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>The train from Venice to the Dolomites is one of those journeys where the destination keeps revealing itself in stages. First the flatlands of the Veneto, all vineyards and villas. Then the foothills, gentle rises that barely register. And then, suddenly, the mountains—not rising from the landscape but erupting from it, great vertical walls of pale dolomite that glow pink at sunrise and orange at sunset and impossible at all times.</p>

                <p>The Dolomites are not the Alps. They're older, stranger, more dramatic. These are the mountains that inspired Tolkien's Misty Mountains, that convinced Le Corbusier that nature could teach architecture, that make even the most jaded travelers stop mid-sentence and just stare. We're giving them four nights, split between two very different experiences.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="full-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519681393784-d120267933ba?w=1400&q=80" 
                     alt="Dolomites peaks in winter" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>The Tre Cime di Lavaredo at sunset, the Dolomites' most iconic peaks</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>First, <strong>Cortina d'Ampezzo</strong>—the queen of the Dolomites, host of the 1956 Winter Olympics and the 2026 ones too. Cortina is glamorous in the way that old European resorts are glamorous: fur coats and Aperol Spritz, Italian families who've been coming here for generations, a main street where the shopping is as serious as the skiing. But we're not here for the scene. We're here for the <strong>Rosapetra Spa Resort</strong>, a refuge in the hills above town where the mountains fill every window and the thermal pools offer the kind of warmth that soaks into your bones and stays there for days.</p>

                <p>Two nights of spa, of silence, of letting the landscape do the work. Then we move to somewhere even more extraordinary.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="inline-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505932794465-147d1f1b2c97?w=1000&q=80" 
                     alt="Alpe di Siusi in winter" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>Alpe di Siusi: Europe's largest high-altitude meadow, 2,000 meters above sea level</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p><strong>Alpe di Siusi</strong> is Europe's largest alpine meadow—a high plateau of impossible beauty where the grass gives way to snow gives way to sky, and the peaks of the Sassolungo and Sciliar rise at the edges like the walls of some enormous natural cathedral. No cars are allowed up here. The air is so clean it almost hurts. The silence is the kind you can feel in your chest.</p>

                <p>The <strong>COMO Alpina Dolomites</strong> sits in the middle of this meadow, a hotel that somehow manages to be both luxurious and humble. The wellness programs are serious—COMO is known for them—but the real therapy is simpler: wake up, look out the window, remember that places like this exist.</p>

                <p>We'll hike to a <em>rifugio</em> for lunch—one of those mountain huts where they serve polenta and speck and wine that tastes better at altitude than it has any right to. We'll sit on a terrace carved into the snow and watch the peaks catch the afternoon light. And we'll understand, in that way you only understand in mountains, why people spend their whole lives chasing views like this.</p>
            </div>

