        <!-- Milan -->
        <section id="milan">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">IV</span>
                <h2>Milan & Lake Como</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">January 17–23</p>
            </div>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Milan is not a city that tries to charm you. Rome seduces, Florence dazzles, Venice enchants—but Milan just looks at you and waits for you to figure it out. It's a city of closed doors and hidden courtyards, of fashion houses and financial towers, of aperitivo bars where the Negronis are perfect and nobody seems impressed by anything.</p>

                <p>This is also where Italian design was invented. Not the Renaissance kind—the modern kind. The kind that gave us Gio Ponti and Achille Castiglioni, the Triennale and the Salone del Mobile, Kartell and Alessi and B&B Italia. Milan is where form and function learned to dance together, where everyday objects became worthy of museum collections, where "design" stopped being a specialty and became a way of seeing the world.</p>

                <p>We're staying in Ticinese, the neighborhood where the Milanese actually live—the Navigli canals, the vintage shops, the bars that haven't been discovered yet. Our apartment is on Corso di Porta Ticinese, a street that runs from the Roman columns at Piazza Vetra down to the canal district. Five nights. Enough time to stop feeling like tourists.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="full-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1610016302534-6f67f1c968d8?w=1400&q=80" 
                     alt="Fondazione Prada Milan" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>Fondazione Prada: Rem Koolhaas's gold-leafed tower rises above the old distillery</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>The <strong>Fondazione Prada</strong> is the reason we're giving Milan five days. Rem Koolhaas transformed an old distillery into something that feels less like a museum and more like a small city dedicated to art—gold-leafed buildings, a "haunted house" by Robert Gober, a bar designed by Wes Anderson in shades of pink and green and formica. You could spend a full day here and still miss things. We'll have lunch at <strong>Bar Luce</strong>, Anderson's candy-colored café, and pretend we're in a film about people who are cooler than we are.</p>

                <p>The <strong>Pinacoteca di Brera</strong> is the old Milan—Renaissance masterpieces in a former Jesuit college, Raphael and Caravaggio and Piero della Francesca, the kind of collection that would be a national treasure anywhere else but here is just another Tuesday. The <strong>Duomo</strong> is the obvious Milan, but the roof terraces redeem it—two thousand statues and a forest of spires, the Alps visible on clear days, the whole city laid out below like a map of itself.</p>

                <p>And then there's <strong>The Last Supper</strong>. Leonardo's masterpiece, deteriorating on a convent wall in the western part of the city, visible only in fifteen-minute slots that must be booked months in advance. We have tickets for Tuesday morning. Fifteen minutes to stand in front of one of the most famous images in human history and try to see it fresh, to understand why it changed everything that came after it.</p>
            </div>

            <aside class="pull-quote">
                <p>Milan is where form and function learned to dance together.</p>
            </aside>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>On our last full day, we leave the city for <strong>Lake Como</strong>—that improbable body of water shaped like an inverted Y, surrounded by mountains and villas and the kind of beauty that makes you understand why George Clooney bought a house here. We'll take the train to Varenna first, a village so picturesque it looks CGI. Then the ferry to Bellagio, the pearl of the lake, for lunch and wandering. Then Como town and the funicular to Brunate for sunset—the lake laid out below us, the Alps beyond, the light doing things that light shouldn't be able to do.</p>

                <p>One night at the <strong>Hotel Villa Flori</strong>, a villa on the water. In the morning, we cross into Switzerland.</p>
            </div>

