        <!-- Switzerland -->
        <section id="switzerland">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">V</span>
                <h2>Switzerland</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">January 23 – February 1</p>
            </div>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Nine nights in Switzerland, split across five bases. It sounds scattered on paper, but there's a logic to it: we're following the mountains, the trains, and one very specific building.</p>

                <p>First, <strong>Wengen</strong>—a car-free village perched on a sunny terrace in the Bernese Oberland, facing the holy trinity of Swiss peaks: Eiger, Mönch, Jungfrau. No roads reach Wengen. You arrive by cog railway, your bags carried by electric cart, the 21st century fading behind you with every meter of altitude gained. Our apartment has a balcony. The view is the kind they put on chocolate boxes, except it's real and it's ours for three nights.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="full-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531366936337-7c912a4589a7?w=1400&q=80" 
                     alt="Swiss Alps from Wengen" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>The Jungfrau massif seen from Wengen: Eiger, Mönch, and Jungfrau</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Weather permitting, we'll take the train to <strong>Jungfraujoch</strong>—the highest railway station in Europe, 3,454 meters above sea level, where you can walk on a glacier and pretend the whole thing isn't slightly absurd. If the clouds don't cooperate, there's always <strong>Männlichen</strong>, an easier summit with hiking even in January, or the <strong>Lauterbrunnen Valley</strong> below us—that narrow cleft in the mountains where waterfalls drop from cliffs so high they turn to mist before they hit the ground.</p>

                <p><strong>Lucerne</strong> is next—Switzerland's postcard town, the Chapel Bridge and the lake and the mountains rising behind. We're staying at the <strong>AMERON Hotel Flora</strong>, five minutes from everything. One day for the city itself, one day for <strong>Mount Rigi</strong>—the boat to Vitznau, the cogwheel train to the summit, lunch somewhere with a view that never ends. In the evening, maybe the <strong>Rosengart Collection</strong>: Picasso and Klee in a museum small enough to feel intimate.</p>

                <p>And then: <strong>Vals</strong>.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="inline-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1584132967334-10e028bd69f7?w=1000&q=80" 
                     alt="Therme Vals interior" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>Therme Vals: Peter Zumthor's temple to water, stone, and silence</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>Vals is a pilgrimage. Not for everyone—there's almost nothing there, a village of 1,000 people in a valley at the end of a road that goes nowhere else. But for those who care about architecture, about the way light moves through stone, about the idea that a building can be a kind of spiritual experience—Vals is essential.</p>

                <p>The <strong>Therme Vals</strong> is Peter Zumthor's masterpiece, widely considered one of the greatest buildings of the twentieth century. Sixty thousand slabs of local quartzite, layered like sedimentary rock, forming spaces for water and steam and silence. Indoor pools and outdoor pools, hot baths and cold plunges, a drinking fountain that dispenses water straight from the mountain. You move through it slowly, losing track of time, your body temperature rising and falling, the light shifting through narrow windows, the stone warm beneath your feet.</p>

                <p>The <strong>7132 Hotel</strong> wraps around the Therme. Guests get access before and after public hours—those early morning sessions when the pools are empty and the steam rises through shafts of alpine light. We have two nights. We will spend most of them in the water.</p>
            </div>

            <aside class="pull-quote">
                <p>Vals is a pilgrimage. Not for everyone. But for those who care about architecture—essential.</p>
            </aside>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>From Vals, we descend to <strong>Basel</strong>—Switzerland's art city, home to the Kunstmuseum and the Beyeler Foundation and, just across the German border, the <strong>Vitra Design Museum</strong> campus. One night at the <strong>Volkshaus</strong>, a Herzog & de Meuron renovation of a historic building. One day of museums: Vitra's architecture tour in the morning, <strong>Fondation Beyeler</strong> in the afternoon—Renzo Piano's building in a park, one of Europe's great collections of modern art.</p>

                <p>Then <strong>Zürich</strong>, briefly. One night at the <strong>B2 Hotel</strong>, a former brewery turned design hotel. Morning at the <strong>Fraumünster</strong> to see Chagall's stained glass windows, those impossible blues and greens that look like they're lit from within. And then the airport. And then London.</p>
            </div>

