        <section id="london">
            <div class="chapter-header">
                <span class="chapter-number">VI</span>
                <h2>London</h2>
                <p class="chapter-dates">February 1–7</p>
            </div>

            <div class="prose">
                <p>London is the exhale. After five weeks of foreign languages and unfamiliar rhythms, of navigating train stations and decoding menus, of being slightly lost all the time in the best possible way—London is where we land. A city we know. A language we share. A chance to process everything we've seen before we fly home.</p>

                <p>Six nights. No fixed plans. The great London museums are all free: the <strong>Tate Modern</strong> in the Bankside power station, the <strong>V&A</strong> with its endless rooms of beautiful objects, the <strong>British Museum</strong> where every empire eventually ends up donating its treasures. We'll pick and choose based on weather and energy, based on what feels right each morning over coffee.</p>
            </div>

            <figure class="full-image">
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=1400&q=80" 
                     alt="Tower Bridge at dusk" loading="lazy">
                <figcaption>Tower Bridge at twilight: London's most Victorian moment</figcaption>
            </figure>

            <div class="prose">
                <p><strong>Borough Market</strong> for lunch one day, pushing through crowds to find the cheese guy, the oyster bar, the Turkish bakery. <strong>Dover Street Market</strong> for fashion treated as art. <strong>Liberty</strong> for the building itself, that Tudor revival department store with its creaking floors and fabric department that could swallow an afternoon. Maybe a show in the West End. Maybe afternoon tea somewhere ridiculous.</p>

                <p>Our last dinner will be somewhere we love. <strong>Dishoom</strong> for the nostalgia of Bombay cafés. <strong>Hawksmoor</strong> for the kind of steak that makes you forget you've been eating polenta and pasta for a month. <strong>Bao</strong> if we want something that feels like the future.</p>

                <p>And then Heathrow. And then the overnight flight. And then Mexico City in the morning, and everything that comes next.</p>
            </div>

